55":"1355","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England","Kingsbridge, Devon, England":"Kingsbridge, Devon, England","London, England":"London, England","Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1290–1360":"1290–1360","1297–1370":"1297–1370","1323–1355":"1323–1355","1264–Male":"1264–Deceased","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","28 Dec 1315":"28 December 1315","1264":"1264","1297":"1297","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","9 April 1323":"9 April 1323","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1268":"1268","1323":"1323","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England","Kingsbridge, Devon, England":"Kingsbridge, Devon, England","London, England":"London, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wykeham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Wickham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wickham","meanings":["English (southeastern): habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘specialized farm, dairy farm’ + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’, such as Wicham (Kent), Wickham (Berkshire, Essex, Hampshire), Wickhambreux (Kent), Wickhambrook (Suffolk), Wyckham (Sussex), Wycomb (Leicestershire), or Wykeham (Lincolnshire, North Yorkshire). Perhaps also from High Wycombe and West Wycombe (both Buckinghamshire), which had forms in <i>-ham</i> from the 16th century. In some instances, however, <i>wīc-hām</i> is associated with a Romano-British town, and <i>wīc</i> is an adaptation of Latin <i>vicus</i>. This is the case for Wickhambrook in Suffolk, the Roman association probably being the Roman villa at nearby Lidgate. Similarly, Wickham Market, also in Suffolk, is associated with a large Roman settlement in nearby Hacheston. The surname is now also common in Ireland (Wexford), where it was taken in the 17th century.","History: Thomas Wickham is recorded as a freeman of Weathersfield, CT, in 1658."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":47,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Wykeham was born in 1290, in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, his father, John Wykeham, was 26 and his mother, Mary Longe, was 22. He married Mary Terry on 28 December 1315, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1360, in London, England, at the age of 70, and was buried in London, England."},"et":{"1290–1360":"1290–1360","1297–1370":"1297–1370","1323–1355":"1323–1355","1264–Male":"1264–Surnud","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","28 Dec 1315":"28. detsember 1315","1264":"1264","1297":"1297","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","9 April 1323":"9. aprill 1323","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1268":"1268","1323":"1323","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England","Kingsbridge, Devon, England":"Kingsbridge, Devon, England","London, England":"London, England","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–1360":"1290–1360","1297–1370":"1297–1370","1323–1355":"1323–1355","1264–Male":"1264–Kuollut","1268–Female":"1268–Kuollut","28 Dec 1315":"28. joulukuuta 1315","1264":"1264","1297":"1297